'''Cadmus of Miletus''' ({{lang-grc|Κάδμος ὁ Μιλήσιος}}, ''Kádmos ho Milésios'') was according to some ancient authorities, the oldest of the ''[[logographi]]''. Modern scholars who accept this view, assign him to about 550 BC; others regard him as purely mythical. A confused notice in the [[Suda]] mentions three persons of the name: the first, the inventor of the [[alphabet]]; the second, the son of [[Pandion (hero)|Pandion]], according to some the first [[prose]] writer, a little later than [[Orpheus]], author of a history of the foundation of [[Miletus]] and of [[Ionia]] generally, in four books; the third, the son of Archelaus, of later date, author of a history of [[Attica]] in fourteen books, and of some poems of an [[erotic]] character. As [[Dionysius of Halicarnassus]] (''Judicium de Thucydide'', c. 23) distinctly states that the work current in his time under the name of Cadmus was a forgery, it is most probable that the two first are identical with the [[Phoenicia]]n [[Cadmus]], who, as the reputed inventor of letters, was subsequently transformed into the Milesian and the author of an historical work. In this connection it should be observed that the old Milesian nobles traced their descent back to the Phoenician or one of his companions. The text of the notice of the third Cadmus of Miletus in the [[Suda]] is unsatisfactory; and it is uncertain whether he is to be explained in the same way, or whether he was an historical personage, of whom all further record is lost.

