{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox politician (general) |name = Francisco González Guinán |image = Francisco González Guinán BNV.jpg |title= Minister of Development of Venezuela |term_start= 1879 |term_end= 1880 |president= [[Antonio Guzmán Blanco]] |title2= [[Minister of Interior and Justice (Venezuela)|Minister of Home Affairs of Venezuela]] |term_start2= 1887 |term_end2= 1888 |president2= [[Hermógenes López]] |title3= [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Venezuela)|Minister of Foreign Affairs of Venezuela]] |term_start3= 19 December 1908 |term_end3= 13 August 1909 |predecessor3=José de Jesús Paúl |successor3= Juan Pietri |president3= [[Juan Vicente Gómez]] |profession= [[politician]], [[historian]], [[journalist]] |birth_date= {{birth date|df=yes|1841|10|3}} |birth_place= [[Valencia, Venezuela]] |death_date={{death date and age|df=yes|1932|12|7|1841|10|3}} |death_place= [[Macuto, Vargas|Macuto, Venezuela]] |religion=[[Catholicism|Roman Catholic]] |signature =Francisco González Guinán signature.jpg |spouse= }} '''Francisco González Guinán''' (3 October 1841 – 7 December 1932), was a [[Venezuela]]n [[politician]], [[journalist]], [[lawyer]], prominent historian of the 19th century in his country, and one of the main supporters of [[Antonio Guzmán Blanco]].
==Biography== Francisco González Guinán was born on 3 October 1841 in [[Valencia, Venezuela]].{{cn|date=January 2017}} He was a [[historian]], [[journalist]], and [[lawyer]].
He was the [[Minister of Development of Venezuela]] from 1879 until 1880 under [[Antonio Guzmán Blanco]].{{cn|date=January 2017}}
Under president [[Hermógenes López]], he was the 139th [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Venezuela)|Minister of Foreign Affairs of Venezuela]] from 19 December 1908 until 13 August 1909.{{cn|date=January 2017}}
He died 7 December 1932) in [[Macuto, Vargas|Macuto, Venezuela]].{{cn|date=January 2017}}
