{{Infobox scientist |name = Ivo Banac |image = <!--(filename only)--> |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1947|03|01|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Dubrovnik]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|FPR Yugoslavia]] (now Croatia) |death_date = |death_place = |residence = [[United States]]/[[Croatia]] |citizenship = |spouse = [[Andrea Feldman (historian)|Andrea Feldman]] |fields = Historian |workplaces = [[Stanford University]], [[Yale University]], [[Central European University]]<ref name="IRB zaposlenja"/><ref name="Yale"/> |alma_mater = [[Stanford University]], [[Fordham University]]<ref name="IRB izobrazba"/>}}
'''Ivo Banac''' ({{IPA-sh|iːʋo baːnats|hr}}; born 1 March 1947) is a [[Croats|Croatian]] historian, a long-time history professor at [[Yale University]] and was a politician of the former [[Liberal Party (Croatia)|Liberal Party]] in Croatia. {{As of|2012}}, Banac is a consultant for the [[Bosnian Institute]].<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.bosnia.org.uk/about/staff.cfm|title=Bosnian Institute - People|publisher=[[Bosnian Institute]]|accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref>
==Biography== Banac was born in Dubrovnik in 1947. In 1959 he emigrated to the United States with his mother, reuniting with his father who had escaped from Yugoslavia in 1947.<ref name="Nacional20030408">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/13420/ivo-banac-americki-profesor-protiv-balkanskih-politicara |title=Ivo Banac - Američki profesor protiv balkanskih političara |trans-title=Ivo Banac - US professor against Balkan politicians |publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |date=8 April 2003 |last=Bajruši |first=Robert |language=Croatian |accessdate=July 3, 2012 |archivedate=3 July 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68sYYu86a?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/13420/ivo-banac-americki-profesor-protiv-balkanskih-politicara |df= }}</ref> After his father's death in a traffic accident a year later, Ivo lived with his mother in [[New York City]],<ref name="Nacional20030408"/> where he studied history at the [[Fordham University]], graduating in 1969.<ref name="IRB izobrazba">{{Citation|url=http://tkojetko.irb.hr/znanstvenikDetalji.php?sifznan=9771&podaci=izobrazba|title=Ivo Banac - Izobrazba|work=Tko je tko u hrvatskoj znanosti|publisher=[[Ruđer Bošković Institute]]|language=Croatian|accessdate=2009-06-12}}</ref> In the same year Banac moved to [[California]],<ref name="Nacional20030408"/> where he obtained M.Sc. and Ph.D. degrees from the [[Stanford University]].<ref name="IRB izobrazba"/> Although he was a member of [[Students for a Democratic Society]], by his own account he was not attracted by the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]] [[flower power]] movement of the late 1960s.<ref name="Nacional20030408"/>
Banac worked at the Stanford University Department of History and Linguistics from 1972 to 1977,<ref name="IRB zaposlenja">{{Citation|url=http://tkojetko.irb.hr/znanstvenikDetalji.php?sifznan=9771&podaci=zaposlenja|title=Ivo Banac - Zaposlenja|work=Tko je tko u hrvatskoj znanosti|publisher=[[Ruđer Bošković Institute]]|language=Croatian|accessdate=2009-06-12}}</ref> and then moved back to the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] to teach at [[Yale University]]. While at Yale, he earned his [[tenure]], and was a two-time master of [[Pierson College]].<ref name="Nacional20030408"/>
During his stay in the United States, Banac regularly visited Yugoslavia.<ref name="Nacional20030408"/> While visiting Zagreb in 1971, he met [[Vlado Gotovac]] and [[Franjo Tuđman]], who would both become major Croatian political figures after the fall of communism.<ref name="Nacional20030408"/> Banac remained in close contact with Gotovac until his death in 2000;<ref name="Nacional20030408"/> on the other hand, he reportedly didn't think highly of Tuđman, describing him as a person who could not tolerate dissent.<ref name="Nacional20030408"/> Nonetheless, Banac organized Tuđman's lecture at [[Yale University]] in 1990.<ref name="Nacional20030408"/> In 1990, Banac was accepted as an associate member in the [[Croatian Academy of Sciences and Arts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://info.hazu.hr/ivo_banac_biografija|language=Croatian|title=Ivo Banac profile|work=Članovi Akademije|publisher=[[Croatian Academy of Sciences and Arts]]|accessdate=2010-11-29|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100427102712/http://info.hazu.hr/ivo_banac_biografija|archivedate=2010-04-27|df=}}</ref>
Between 1994 and 1999 he was the director of the Institute on Southern Europe at the [[Central European University]], [[Budapest]]. From 1990 onwards, Ivo Banac was also active in Croatian politics. He joined the [[Croatian Social Liberal Party]] (HSLS) and became one of the strongest critics of [[Franjo Tuđman]] and his government, especially with regards to policy towards [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]. He expressed his criticism in a column written for ''[[Feral Tribune]]''. After the HSLS split in 1997, Banac joined the [[Liberal Party (Croatia)|Liberal Party]], keeping a critical distance towards the government even after LS became part of a new governing left-centre coalition in 2000.
He often accused [[Ivica Račan]] of the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia|SDP]] of not doing enough to reverse the negative policies of Tuđman's era. Many were surprised to find Banac, who had a reputation of a maverick and independent intellectual, become the leader of the LS. It was even more surprising to see him take the post of Minister of Environmental Protection in 2003. He held that post for only a few months, until the SDP - the party with whom the LS was aligned - lost the election to a rejuvenated HDZ. {{citation needed|date=October 2013}}
He was elected to the Croatian Parliament in the [[Croatian parliamentary election, 2003]].<ref name="Sabor"/> After the elections, Banac advocated a merger of all liberal parties in Croatia. This policy was opposed by [[Zlatko Kramarić]] who orchestrated Banac's removal from the party leadership in 2004. Banac left the LS in February 2005 and was an independent representative in the [[Sabor]] for the rest of his term.<ref name="Sabor">{{cite web|url=http://www.sabor.hr/Default.aspx?sec=298|language=Croatian|title=Ivo Banac - nezavisni|work=Zastupnici 5. saziva Hrvatskoga sabora|publisher=[[Croatian Parliament]]|accessdate=2010-11-29}}</ref> He was publicly criticized for having allegedly mishandled public funds, by renting his personal apartment to himself as office space, as well as furnishing it with taxpayers money.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/ovo-su-ljudi-koji-cuvaju-ugled-sabora/195947|language=Croatian|newspaper=[[Jutarnji list]]|title=Ovo su ljudi koji čuvaju ugled Sabora|date=2009-02-24|accessdate=2010-11-29|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213232521/http://www.jutarnji.hr/ovo-su-ljudi-koji-cuvaju-ugled-sabora/195947|archivedate=2012-02-13|df=}}</ref> Banac replied, to accusations that such actions constitute mishandling of public funds, that while "the data published in the media are correct, it is all a matter of interpretation, is the glass half full or half empty".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/novosti/hrvatska/clanak/id/22351/banac-o-tome-kako-je-sam-sebi-iznajmio-poslovni-prostor-sve-je-legalno|language=Croatian|newspaper=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|title=Banac o tome kako je sam sebi iznajmio poslovni prostor: Sve je legalno!|date=2008-09-23|accessdate=2016-04-29}}</ref> Between 2007 and 2009, Banac was the President of the [[Croatian Helsinki Committee]].
At Yale, he is the Bradford Durfee Professor of History Emeritus.<ref name="Yale">{{Citation|url=http://www.yale.edu/history/faculty/banac.html|title=Ivo Banac|work=www.yale.edu|publisher=[[Yale University]]|accessdate=2010-11-29|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821060144/http://www.yale.edu/history/faculty/banac.html|archivedate=2010-08-21|df=}}</ref> He also served as the director of the Council on [[European Studies]] at [[Yale University]].
