{{Infobox museum |name = Jebel Barkal Museum |image = JebelBarkalMuseum1.jpg |imagesize = |caption = Statue representing a row of four baboons. [[Kingdom of Kush#Napatan period|Napatan period]] from [[Taharqa]] temple at [[Sanam, Sudan|Sanam]] |pushpin_map = |map_caption = Location of the Jebel Barkal Museum, Sudan |coordinates = {{coord|18|31|58.2|N|31|49|42.5|E|display=inline,title}} |established = 1979 |dissolved = |location = Archaeological site of [[Jebel Barkal]], {{flag|Sudan}} |type = Archaeological collection |visitors = |director = |curator = |publictransit = |website = {{URL|http://jebel-barkal-museum.museum.com}} }}
The '''Jebel Barkal Museum''' is an archaeological site museum located on the eastern side of the archeological area of [[Jebel Barkal]] at [[Karima, Sudan|Karima]] in the [[Northern state, Sudan|Northern State]] of [[Sudan]].<ref> Maria Constanza de Simone; Nubia and Nubians: The ‘Museumization’ of a Culture; Leiden University 2014; p.142.</ref><ref>[http://www.unesco.org/new/en/culture/themes/museums/museum-projects/archive/preservation-of-endangered-objects-at-the-national-museum-of-sudan-and-the-archaeological-museum-of-jebel-barkal/ UNESCO report: Preservation of Endangered Objects at the National Museum of Sudan and the Archaeological Museum of Jebel Barkal.]</ref>
==Displays== [[File:JebelBarkalMuseum2.jpg|thumb|left|Stela with [[Meroitic alphabet|meroitic inscriptions]] for [[Natakamani]] and [[Amanitore]]]] The three gallery rooms of the museum display artefacts and pottery findings from excavations conducted in the Jebel Barkal area, among them one of the royal [[Twenty-fifth Dynasty of Egypt]] statues found by [[George A. Reisner]] in 1916<ref>[http://www.jebelbarkal.org/frames/B500statues.pdf The finding of the Jebel Barkal statues.]</ref>.
